LX.. ¹ Propuqnare, aut parare, &c.] The reading in the other edi— tions is obpuynare, aut parare, &c. Anthon says the former of these two verbs, namely, oppuynare, or obpuynare, refers to the Romans, the latter to the Numidians. “They prosecuted the attack, or resisted the assailants.” “ After parare understand defensionem.'’ Altogether in error, as usual. Where is the word defensio understood? Why has he not given an example of the ellipsis of this word? He could not: it is never understood. And Boyd is silent here.
